snippet.textDisplay:
I'm a retired Park Ranger, and the for about 12 years of my career I lived and worked in a ghost town that had been rebuilt and contained several shops and attractions for tourism. A few of the adobe buildings and one of the wooden ones were original buildings that had somehow survived the elements, vandals and souvenir/treasure hunters for over 100 years until the town site was rebuilt and made into a tourist attraction and then later a Regional Park and then protected and maintained. These original buildings were, of course, historical landmarks that had been made into shops, museums and offices after being restored, and each had a small placard from the Historical Society and a sign explaining that these buildings were not mock-ups, but original structures that were part of the town more than 100 years ago. Likewise, there was a sign at the entrance of the cemetery, located a couple of hundred yards from the town, that explained there were really people buried there and the tombstones were all real - even the wooden ones. Over the years that I was there, I caught a LOT of people vandalizing park property or trying to take a souvenir.

Of all the times I caught people (of all ages and nationalities) carving their name into something or trying to steal (or sometimes just break, for no reason other than just to destroy) something, 99.9% of the time it was either an original building or one of the graves in the cemetery. I have caught boy scouts (and even scout leaders), senior citizens, rich people, poor people, tour guides from bus tours, even school teachers on field trips and once a fairly well known local medical doctor, all doing things that, when caught in the act, even they were sometimes surprised at their own actions. Most were even embarrassed - not for being caught doing something wrong, but for WHAT they were doing wrong when they got caught. The most common excuse I got from the Americans was, "I just wanted to leave my mark. Something that I could show my kids in ten or twenty years to prove I had been here." I told them there were other ways to leave proof of your previous visitation and that next time they might try taking photos or buying something from one of the gift shops (not stealing a wagon wheel or any of the other artifacts on display [either in an enclosed case or bolted down] for EVERYONE to see and enjoy). I told them they could plant a tree or donate a park bench and we would put a little sign on it with their name, month and year of the donation on it as evidence of their generosity. They could even volunteer their time and spend a day or two working with us - or even longer because we have VIP (Volunteer In Park) programs like our Campground Host program where they get a summer of free camping in a full hook-up RV site in return for something like 20 hours per week of volunteer time (usually collecting camping fees or collecting day use fees at the main entrance gate).

snippet.textDisplay: When I was a kid, I was on a school field trip to an art museum in an old Victorian mansion, that happened to be alongside railroad tracks. Being the kid I was, trains were super cool and much more interesting than the art installations. So when one passed, I had to get as close as I could, and as close as I could get was the museum's original fence line. It was a wooden fence, about 4 feet high, definitely an aesthetic fixture. So when I ran to the fence at full gallop, and used it to stop myself, the whole thing toppled over and I ran away. And I think about that a lot.
